history.content:
Regarding whether it's manageable: yes I think so. Not a walk in the park and it depends on your prior course load, but you'll probably be fine.

I don't think there's a real benefit to taking 140 over 126 if you want a more manageable workload since they're both high workload classes; as a reference point I spent ~40-50% more time woking on 140 than 127 in the respective semesters where I took those classes. I think the key questions you should be asking yourself are:

1) Am I confident with the probability material from 70? If so, take 126

2) Am I interested more in probability theory and statistics or its applications in stochastic processes? 140 for the former, 126 for the latter
